library(RCurl)
## Loading required package: bitops
download <- getURL("https://www.epa.gov/sites/production/files/2014-10/wsa_siteinfo_ts_final.csv")
wsa <- read.csv(text = download)
class(wsa)
## [1] "data.frame"
wsa <- st_as_sf(wsa, coords = c("LON_DD", "LAT_DD"), crs = 4269,agr = "constant") #import data as a sf, proj4string all have a code, in this case it is '4269' . EPASG code!

#if you want to plot the column, not just the geomtry (also makes ure to specfiy columns or else will do all!)
plot(wsa[c('ECOWSA9','HUC8')], graticule = st_crs(wsa), axes=TRUE) # can use categorial or continous

# Can also summarize the data to show
levels(wsa$ECOWSA9) #will tell us how many levels are in the dataset, and lists the levels within the column
## [1] "CPL" "NAP" "NPL" "SAP" "SPL" "TPL" "UMW" "WMT" "XER"
wsa_plains <- wsa[wsa$ECOWSA9 %in% c("TPL","NPL","SPL"), ] #pulls out the plains can use this in the columns as well 
plot(wsa$geometry)
plot(wsa_plains$geometry, col='red', add=T) #plot just the plains today 

#NOw we want to 
library(USAboundaries)
states  <- us_states()
levels(as.factor(states$state_abbr)) #lists all the levels! Notice it has puerto Rico, Hawaii, and Alaska, we dont want those. 
##  [1] "AK" "AL" "AR" "AZ" "CA" "CO" "CT" "DC" "DE" "FL" "GA" "HI" "IA" "ID"
## [15] "IL" "IN" "KS" "KY" "LA" "MA" "MD" "ME" "MI" "MN" "MO" "MS" "MT" "NC"
## [29] "ND" "NE" "NH" "NJ" "NM" "NV" "NY" "OH" "OK" "OR" "PA" "PR" "RI" "SC"
## [43] "SD" "TN" "TX" "UT" "VA" "VT" "WA" "WI" "WV" "WY"
states <- states[!states$state_abbr %in% c('AK','PR','HI'),] #remove non-continental states to tighten bounaries

# Check for equal CRS
st_crs(states) == st_crs(wsa_plains) #are the cooridinate systems of the two layers st_crs
## [1] FALSE
#false so lets transform the data 
wsa_plains <- st_transform(wsa_plains, st_crs(states))

plot(states$geometry, axes=TRUE)
plot(wsa_plains$geometry, col='blue',add=TRUE)

#Now we want to select out the states that intercept with the plain data points.

plains_states <- states[wsa_plains,] #Yes!!! selection based on the matching of two layers. Looks like a selection based on just rows, so only just based on geomtry, very cool. 
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
plot(plains_states$geometry, axes=T)

# plains_states <- states[wsa_plains,op = st_intersects] #Could also to it like that!

# Use column indexing to subset just a couple attribute columns - need to keep geometry column!
wsa_plains <- wsa_plains[c(1:4,60)]
wsa_plains <- st_join(wsa_plains, plains_states) #join two layers
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
# verify your results
plot(plains_states$geometry, axes=T)
plot(wsa_plains['state_abbr'], add = T, pch=19)
